STREPTOCOCCUS, GROUP A - CANADA: (QUEBEC) FATAL, SENIORS' RESIDENCES, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*********************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 1 Sep 2022 07:47 EDT
Source: CTV News [edited]
http://montreal.ctvnews.ca/4-dead-after-strep-a-outbreak-in-montreal-seniors-residence-1.6049837


Four people are dead after an outbreak of group A streptococcal disease (GAS) at a private seniors' residence (RPA) in Montreal's west end. According to Montreal public health officials, there are 6 confirmed cases of infection at Les Résidences Floralies in Lachine.

Officials insist they cannot comment on specifics, but did confirm that the outbreak has already spread to a 2nd seniors' home, Les Résidences Floralies in LaSalle, where at least one case has been detected.

"At this time, Montreal public health is closely monitoring the situation and an epidemiological investigation is underway," said Jean Nicolas Aubé, a spokesperson with the Integrated University Health and Social Services Center of the Centre-Sud-de-l'Île-de-Montréal.

This isn't the 1st time the Résidence Les Floralies has seen a strep A outbreak in its facility. In February 2019, the home in LaSalle was told by Accreditation Canada that it had to create a plan to detect infections and create a pandemic protocol after 3 seniors died due to the disease.

One year later, the private residence was hit hard by COVID-19, with at least 18 residents dying during the 1st wave.

Questions are now being raised about how vigilant monitoring at these facilities is, with the provincial government opening an investigation into the quality of care. The company did not respond to CTV News' request for comment on Wednesday [31 Aug 2022].

According to infectious diseases specialist Dr. Matthew Oughton, the strep A bacteria are easily detectable and can be a common occurrence in healthcare settings. "[It is] relatively easy to treat, but can be aggressive," he said, noting infections can range from minor to life-threatening. "[It is] highly transmissible and can lead to complications and be invasive."

He points to former Quebec premier Lucien Bouchard, who, after being infected with the disease, lost his leg to necrotizing fasciitis, a flesh-eating condition. "When we see an outbreak, we must take steps to screen transmission and decide who needs to be isolated and treated," said Oughton.

Residents in the affected facilities must be monitored for signs and symptoms of infection, including fever, sore throat, pain and change in mental status, adds infectious diseases specialist Dr. Donald Vinh. "If that's the situation for some of the individuals in these residences, immediate medical attention should be sought," he said.

Aubé noted management at the 2 homes are cooperating with health authorities to curb the outbreaks.

[Byline: Rachel Lau]

