Communicated by:
ProMED

[Group A streptococcus (GAS), also called _Streptococcus pyogenes_, are gram-positive cocci that grow in chains. Most often, GAS cause localized superficial infections, such as pharyngitis ("strep throat") or impetigo, which may be complicated by scarlet fever, when strains of GAS produce bacteriophage-encoded erythrogenic exotoxin that is responsible for the skin rash of the infection. These toxin-producing strains cause scarlet fever in people who do not already have antitoxin antibodies. Over a century ago, scarlet fever was feared as a potentially lethal complication of GAS. Its mortality and morbidity waned, however, well before antibiotics became available. Since the advent of antibiotic therapy, the mortality rate of treated scarlet fever has been less than 1%.

Sometimes, GAS invade the lungs (pneumonia), blood (bacteremia), the nervous system (meningitis), cause toxic shock syndrome, or spread along the layers of soft tissue that surround muscle (fasciitis). These infections are called invasive group A streptococcal (iGAS) disease and are very serious, even life-threatening, and may account for the high case fatality rate in this Montreal outbreak. However, we are not told what types of GAS infection are involved in this outbreak.

Predisposing factors for iGAS infection include influenza for pneumonia, and skin lesions, poor personal hygiene, crowding in shelters for the homeless, and injection drug use for necrotizing fasciitis. The patients in the Montreal outbreak reportedly are elderly nursing home residents and if bedridden may have had pressure ulcers, also called decubitus ulcers, that could become secondarily infected with GAS.

M protein is the major virulence factor of GAS, which are divided into serotypes based on the antigenic differences in the M protein molecule. More recently, GAS are typed on the basis of sequence analysis of the portion of the _emm_ gene that encodes M serospecificity (http://medbox.iiab.me/modules/en-cdc/www.cdc.gov/streplab/m-proteingene-typing.html). The news report does not specify the M protein types that are involved in the current outbreak. Other molecular techniques to further characterize outbreak strains include pulse-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE) of chromosomal DNA fragments, multilocus sequence typing (MLST), detection of exotoxin-encoding genes, and whole genome sequencing. Molecular typing of isolates may aid in documenting whether the Montreal outbreak is caused by a common "outbreak" strain or if multiple different strains are involved.

Les Résidences Floralies in Lachine and LaSalle are assisted living residences for seniors (https://residencesfloralies.qc.ca/en/). Lachine (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lachine,_Quebec) and LaSalle (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LaSalle,_Quebec) are adjacent boroughs (arrondissements) within the city of Montreal on the Island of Montreal in southwestern Quebec, Canada. A map showing the location of these boroughs can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Lachine,+Montreal,+QC,+Canada.

More information on this outbreak from knowledgeable sources would be appreciated. - Mod.ML

